$$source: 8.01 Lecture 31
$$title: Forced Oscillations and Resonance


 <math> ma = -kx + F_o cos(\omega t) </math> &omega; is frequency of choice

 <math>\ddot{x} + \frac{k}{m} x = \frac{F_o}{m} cos(\omega t)</math>

 Steady state: <math>x = A cos \omega t</math>

 <math>A\left(\frac{k}{m} - \omega^2\right) = \frac{F_0}{m}</math> and <math>\omega_0^2 = \frac{k}{m}</math>
 (free oscillation) so  
 <math>A=\frac{\frac{F_0}{m}}{\omega_0^2 - \omega^2}</math>

 if <math>\omega \lt\lt \omega_0 \quad a = \frac{F_0}{k}</math>

 if <math>\omega >> \omega_0 \quad A \rightarrow 0</math>

 if <math>\omega = \omega_0 \quad A \rightarrow \infty</math> (resonance)

 A system has as many resonant frequencies as masses in the system  
 A string is equivalent to infinite number of masses

 resonant frequencies - harmonics - <math>f_n = n f_1</math>

 in a tube - <math> f_n = \frac{nv}{2L}</math>

 Breaking a wine glass demo at ~40:00

 Tacoma narrows footage at ~42:00
